<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Adjacency Matrix</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/GraphTheory/AdjacencyMat=
rix.nb" download=3D"AdjacencyMatrix.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfr=
am.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27=
" alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The adjacency matrix, sometimes also called the connection matrix, of a sim=
ple labeled graph is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Matrix.html=
">matrix</a> with rows and columns labeled by <a href=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/GraphVertex.html">graph vertices</a>, with a 1 or 0 in position=
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix=
/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"48" height=3D"25" alt=3D"(v_i,v_j)"> according to=
 whether <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjacen=
cyMatrix/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"v_i"> and <img s=
rc=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline=
3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bor=
der=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"24" alt=3D"v_j"> are <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/AdjacentVertices.html">adjacent</a> or not.
 For a simple graph with no self-loops, the adjacency matrix must have 0s o=
n the diagonal.
 For an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/UndirectedGraph.html">undi=
rected graph</a>, the adjacency matrix
 is <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SymmetricMatrix.html">symmetri=
c</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"412.924" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/AdjacencyMatrix_1002.svg" class=
=3D"" alt=3D"AdjacencyMatrix">
</div>
<p>
The illustration above shows adjacency matrices for particular labelings of=
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ClawGraph.html">claw graph</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/CycleGraph.html">cycle graph</a=
> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatri=
x/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"19" height=3D"21" alt=3D"C_4">, and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://mathworld.wolfram.com/CompleteGraph.html">complete
 graph</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjac=
encyMatrix/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"20" height=3D"21" alt=3D"K_4">.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"412.924" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/AdjacencyMatrices_1002.svg" class=
=3D"" alt=3D"AdjacencyMatrices">
</div>
<p>
Since the labels of a graph may be permuted without changing the underlying=
 graph being represented, there are in general multiple possible adjacency =
matrices corresponding
 to a given simple graph. In particular, the number <img src=3D"https://mat=
hworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline6.svg" class=3D"i=
nlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=
=3D"48" height=3D"21" alt=3D"N_A(G)"> of distinct adjacency matrices for a =
simple unlabeled
 graph <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjacency=
Matrix/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"G">
 with <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/VertexCount.html">vertex cou=
nt</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjacency=
Matrix/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"51" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D|G|"> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AutomorphismGroup.html">automorphism g=
roup</a>
 order <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjacency=
Matrix/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"62" height=3D"21" alt=3D"|Aut(G)|">
 is given by
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequat=
ion" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"110" he=
ight=3D"42" alt=3D" N_A=3D(|G|!)/(|Aut(G)|), "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyM=
atrix/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wi=
dth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=3D"|G|!">
 is the number or permutations of vertex labels. The illustration above sho=
ws the
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix=
/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"67" height=3D"21" alt=3D"4!/8=3D3"> possible adj=
acency matrices of
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/CycleGraph.html">cycle graph<=
/a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMat=
rix/Inline12.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"19" height=3D"21" alt=3D"C_4">.
</p>
<p>
The adjacency matrix of a labeled <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com=
/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline13.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" sty=
le=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21=
" alt=3D"n">-<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Digraph.html">digraph=
</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMa=
trix/Inline14.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"14" height=3D"21" alt=3D"D"> is the binary <=
a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SquareMatrix.html">square matrix</a=
>
 of order <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjace=
ncyMatrix/Inline15.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">
 whose <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adjacency=
Matrix/Inline16.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-w=
idth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"33" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(i,j)">th
 entry is 1 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Iff.html">iff</a> <img=
 src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inli=
ne17.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"33" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(i,j)"> is an edge of <img s=
rc=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline=
18.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"14" height=3D"21" alt=3D"D">.
</p>
<p>
The adjacency matrix of a graph can be computed in the <a href=3D"http://ww=
w.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> using <tt><a href=3D"http://r=
eference.wolfram.com/language/ref/AdjacencyMatrix.html">AdjacencyMatrix</a>=
</tt>[<i>g</i>],
 with the result being returned as a sparse array.
</p>
<p>
A different version of the adjacency is sometimes defined in which diagonal=
 elements are <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Ad=
jacencyMatrix/Inline19.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"51" height=3D"22" alt=3D"a_(ii)=3D0=
">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMa=
trix/Inline20.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"53" height=3D"24" alt=3D"a_(ij)=3D1">
 if <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMat=
rix/Inline21.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-widt=
h:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"v_i">
 and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/AdjacencyMa=
trix/Inline22.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"24" alt=3D"v_j">
 are adjacent and <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height=
:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"21" height=3D"21" alt=3D"-1">
 otherwise (e.g., Goethals and Seidel 1970).
</p>
<p>
A <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/WeightedAdjacencyMatrix.html">we=
ighted adjacency matrix</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/image=
s/equations/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"21" height=3D"24" alt=
=3D"A_f"> of a simple graph can also be defined for a real positive
 symmetric function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equati=
ons/AdjacencyMatrix/Inline25.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heig=
ht:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"66" height=3D"25" alt=3D"f(d_=
i,d_j)">
 on the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/VertexDegree.html">vertex =
degrees</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Adja=
cencyMatrix/Inline26.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;=
max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"14" height=3D"21" alt=3D"d_i"> of a g=
raph (Das <i>et al. </i>2018, Zheng <i>et al. </i>2022).
</p>
